Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
How flexible are NCBI searches with respect to misspellings?\xA0 Is it necessary to spell every word completely correctly, or do the search tools recognize single letter misspellings as Google does?

Instructor's Post

Title: Linking forum posts - bioinfomethods-01-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: Slide 26 no 'links' for BRCA1- here is a fix
Input.posts:
The layout of the pages seems to have changed slightly- it happens all the time with these database, something to get used to. \xA0 As mentioned in another post, to get the same result as in the lecture from the OMIM result page you have to select the 'gene summaries' under BRCA1 and then from the menu on the right hand side select 'SNP: gene view'. \xA0 In addition, when the dbSNP short genetic variations page is returned make sure that the 'in gene region' button rather than the 'cSNP' on the option bar part way down is selected. Then select refresh. It should look pretty much like slide 27 now.
Upvotes:
5
Just to follow-up on Victoria's very helpful post emphasizing that things are always in flux as the science and tech evolves, Christmas eve the Genome Reference Consortium released a new human genome assembly, see about it here. \xA0 However, I do not think that is contributing to the differences we see with the SNP above the one corresponding to the position of amino acid1824 because the page presently refers to assembly\xA0 GRCh37, which is not the latest . \xA0If we consider the human genome further as the course progresses, the specific assembly being considered will be something to keep in mind.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Blerg, yes, good points Victoria and Wayne. Indeed given the ease of generating sequence data, it is not surprising the NCBI has revamped there DBs for this kind of thing (there's also a dbVar, which documents more kinds of changes, not just SNPs, but insertions, copy number variants, and deletions, and this might also be useful to refer to for the kind of mock problem I present in the lecture), and they have certainly moved things around since I recorded the lecture in the summer, when I did check that things were working. I may not have updated some slides from the undergrad course this course is based on if the info was more or less the same. The point is that there is a wealth of info at NCBI and it pays to poke around!

Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
I believe that slide 22 related to briefly explaining the evolutionary relationships between genes related by sequence similarity, and a quick explanation of the various terms used to describe these relationships: homolog, ortholog and paralog. Paralog refers to duplicate copies of a gene in the genome of a species, in this case the mouse alpha globin chain gene and mouse beta globin chain gene can be thought of as paralogs of one another. Orthologs are genes that occurred due to speciation, so after the early globin chain gene duplicated into alpha chain and beta chain globin genes, the genes were found in different species. In this case, mouse, frog and chick alpha chain globin genes are orthologs of each other. Homolog is the all-encompassing term used to describe paralogs and orthologs.
